\f2\b\fs36 \cf0 Chapter 3: The Earth Witch\'92s Truth
\f0\b0\fs24 \
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\fi576\sl360\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1 \cf0 Sacred Earth Botanicals was a haven of life even in the heart of winter. The garden thrived with a vibrancy that made Marisol\'92s heart ache with longing. Terra cotta pots brimming with desert flora lined the pathways\'97ocotillo stretching skyward, marigolds defying the season with their vibrant blooms, and cacti adorned with unexpected flowers.\
Marisol hesitated at the gate, her gaze trailing to Moira, whose presence beside her felt reassuring. Together, they stepped through the iron entrance, the scent of creosote and sage embracing them like a warm, familiar blanket. Beneath these scents lingered something else\'97an electric tang, almost like the air before a storm.\
Brenda Knight was tending to a young ocotillo, her hands moving with practiced grace that seemed to guide the plant\'92s growth. Her silver-streaked braid swung gently as she moved, and the plants around her seemed to pulse with the same energy.\
"You\'92re brave, coming here after what happened last night," Brenda said without looking up. Her voice held a note of acknowledgment rather than reproach.\
Marisol squared her shoulders, her resolve bolstered by Moira\'92s steady presence at her side. "I need to understand what happened. Why my magic didn\'92t work."\
Brenda finally looked up, her eyes meeting Marisol\'92s with a depth that seemed to see right through her. "The land isn\'92t something to be controlled, Marisol. It\'92s something to be in harmony with."\
Marisol glanced at a marigold, its petals shimmering with life that had eluded her own craft. "Your plants are thriving. How?"\
"The land\'92s magic doesn\'92t fail\'97it withdraws when it\'92s out of balance," Brenda said, touching the soil with reverence. "Magic is a partnership, not a dictatorship."\
Moira stepped closer, her gaze shifting between Brenda and Marisol. "The trails have been different too. The deer, the birds... even the plants are behaving strangely."\
Brenda nodded, acknowledging Moira\'92s observations with a respect that Marisol hadn\'92t noticed before. "The signs are everywhere if you know how to listen. The land speaks in many voices."\
Marisol frowned, the weight of her grandmother's teachings settling heavily on her shoulders. "I thought I was listening. But... maybe I was too focused on the spells."\
Brenda\'92s expression softened. "Your grandmother knew that spells are just one part of magic. She listened first, then acted. That\'92s why her magic was so powerful."\
The morning sun caught in Moira's hair as she bent to examine a cluster of marigolds. "So, what do we do? How do we help restore balance?"\
Brenda smiled, a gesture that seemed to light up her entire face. "We listen. We bring together what\'92s been divided\'97wild magic and crafted spells. And we remember that the land must be willing."\
Marisol nodded slowly, understanding dawning like the morning light. "I want to help, but I don\'92t know how to bridge that gap."\
"That\'92s why we work together," Brenda said, her voice imbued with an unshakeable confidence. "Each of us brings something unique to the table."\
Moira straightened, her eyes meeting Marisol\'92s with a warmth that spread through Marisol like a healing balm. "We\'92ve got your back."\
As they prepared to leave, Brenda handed Marisol a small, clay pot containing a seedling, its roots wrapped in dark, rich soil. "Feel this," she instructed. "Let it teach you. Magic isn\'92t just about power\'97it\'92s about connection."\
Marisol cradled the pot, the soil cool against her palms. Something within the seedling pulsed gently, a rhythm that matched her heartbeat. It was an invitation, a promise of what could be if she was willing to listen.\
"Thank you," Marisol said, her voice carrying a newfound resolve. "I\'92ll see you both at dawn."\
Together, they left the garden, stepping back into the crisp winter air. Marisol felt a sense of purpose settle over her, the path ahead illuminated not just by the morning sun, but by the understanding and support of those walking beside her.\
